<h1 style="color: rgb(253, 17, 0);">Information</h1>
<p>
  <h3 style="color: rgb(233, 232, 238);"> Background Information
    Film Origin: The Moana film was produced by Walt Disney Animation Studios and released in November 2016. It was directed by Ron Clements and John Musker, with songs by Lin-Manuel Miranda, Opetaia Foa'i, and Mark Mancina.
    
    Stage Adaptation: In 2020, it was announced that a live stage production of Moana would be coming to Broadway. The show would be based on the movie's story and music but with additional staging, new songs, and a reimagined script. The project was in development under Disney Theatrical Productions, the same team behind Broadway hits like The Lion King and Aladdin.
    
    Key Information About the Show
    Premiere: The Moana stage show was initially set to premiere at Disneys Aulani resort in Hawaii, and plans for a Broadway debut were in the works. Due to the global pandemic, the full-scale Broadway production was delayed, but Disney announced they would continue developing the stage adaptation.
    
    Music: The stage version will feature all the iconic songs from the film, such as How Far Ill Go and Youre Welcome, along with some new songs to enrich the live theater experience. The music, as in the film, will be heavily influenced by Polynesian culture, with a mix of traditional instruments and modern musical elements.
    
    Story: Like the film, the stage production of Moana tells the story of a young girl named Moana, the daughter of a Polynesian chief, who is chosen by the ocean to restore the heart of Te Fiti, an ancient artifact that was stolen by the demigod Maui. Along the way, she encounters various challenges, learns about her true self, and builds her courage to become a leader.</h3>
</p>

<h1 style="color: rgb(255, 0, 0);"> information</h1>
<p>
 <h3 style="color: beige;">
  Original Story - "Aladdin and the Magic Lamp"
  Origins: The story of Aladdin is set in China (in some versions, it's set in a fictional city in the Middle East), and it first appeared in One Thousand and One Nights, a collection of Middle Eastern folktales. However, the tale of Aladdin was not originally part of the Arabic text but was added later by a French translator, Antoine Galland, in the early 18th century.
  
  Plot: The story follows a poor young man named Aladdin, who lives with his widowed mother. One day, a sorcerer from the Maghreb convinces Aladdin's mother that he is a wealthy prince who can marry her daughter. The sorcerer tricks Aladdin into entering a magical cave to retrieve a lamp. Aladdin finds a genie (or a magical spirit) inside the lamp who can grant him wishes.
  
  With the help of the genie, Aladdin becomes rich and powerful. He wins the love of Princess Jasmine (in some versions of the tale), but trouble arises when the sorcerer tries to steal the lamp for himself. In the end, Aladdin defeats the sorcerer, secures his happiness with the princess, and lives a prosperous life.
